{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"MySQL Constraints","slug":"mysql-constraints","subject":"MySQL","category":"Database","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["MySQL Tables"],"learning_objectives":["Understand Constraints","PRIMARY KEY","NOT NULL","UNIQUE","DEFAULT","FOREIGN KEY"],"theory":"## Ensuring Data Integrity\nConstraints are rules enforced on data columns. They ensure the accuracy and reliability of the data.\n\n### Common Constraints\n1. **NOT NULL**: Ensures a column cannot have a NULL value.\n2. **UNIQUE**: Ensures all values in a column are different.\n3. **PRIMARY KEY**: A combination of NOT NULL and UNIQUE. Uniquely identifies each row. Only one per table.\n4. **FOREIGN KEY**: Uniquely identifies a row/record in *another* table. Links two tables.\n5. **DEFAULT**: Sets a default value if none is specified.\n6. **CHECK**: Ensures values satisfy a specific condition (e.g., Age >= 18).","syntax":"CREATE TABLE table_name (\n    col1 type CONSTRAINTS,\n    ...\n    PRIMARY KEY (col1)\n);","examples":[{"code":"CREATE TABLE students (\n    id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE,\n    name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    age INT CHECK (age >= 18),\n    status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'active'\n);","output":"Table created","explanation":"Validates data: ID is unique/mandatory, Email must be unique, Name is mandatory, Age must be adult, Status defaults to 'active'."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Inserting duplicate values into a Primary Key.","correction":"Will cause error: Duplicate entry 'x' for key 'PRIMARY'.","example":"Inserting ID 1 twice."},{"mistake":"Inserting NULL into NOT NULL column.","correction":"Will cause error: Column 'x' cannot be null.","example":"N/A"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"Can a table have multiple Primary Keys?","answer":"No. A table can have only ONE Primary Key. However, that primary key can consist of multiple columns (Composite Primary Key).","difficulty":"Medium"},{"question":"Difference between Primary Key and Unique Key?","answer":"Primary Key imposes NOT NULL constraint automatically. Unique Key allows NULL values (usually one NULL, depending on DB). A table can have multiple Unique Keys but only one Primary Key.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"User Registration","description":"Email must be UNIQUE to prevent duplicate accounts. Password must be NOT NULL. Created_at usually has a DEFAULT of current_timestamp.","code":"N/A"}],"exam_notes":["Constraints = Rules.","PK = Unique + Not Null.","FK = Link to other table.","Check constraints valid from MySQL 8.0.16+."],"summary":"Constraints are vital for data quality. They prevent invalid data from entering the system at the database level.","order":41},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"mysql-introduction-to-databases","path":"content/mysql/mysql-introduction-to-databases.json","title":"Introduction to Databases","category":"Database","subject":"MySQL","description":"","order":1},{"slug":"mysql-introduction","path":"content/mysql/mysql-introduction.json","title":"Introduction to MySQL","category":"Database","subject":"MySQL","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"mysql-installation","path":"content/mysql/mysql-installation.json","title":"MySQL Installation & Setup","category":"Database","subject":"MySQL","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"mysql-security","path":"content/mysql/mysql-security.json","title":"MySQL Security Basics","category":"Database","subject":"MySQL","description":"","order":4},{"slug":"mysql-architecture","path":"content/mysql/mysql-architecture.json","title":"MySQL Architecture","category":"Database","subject":"MySQL","description":"","order":5},{"slug":"mysql-backup-restore","path":"content/mysql/mysql-backup-restore.json","title":"MySQL Backup & Restore","category":"Database","subject":"MySQL","description":"","order":6},{"slug":"mysql-best-practices","path":"content/mysql/mysql-best-practices.json","title":"MySQL Best Practices","cate